Panic Detection Algorithm Outline

Core Concept
A swimmer in distress exhibits sustained, rapid, irregular motion in a confined area — unlike normal swimming which is rhythmic and travels across zones. The algorithm exploits this difference.

Step 1 — Background Establishment
- Capture first N frames on startup
- Build a static background model of the empty/calm pool
- This becomes the baseline reference

Step 2 — Per Frame Grid Analysis
- Divide frame into grid (e.g. 10x10 cells)
- For each cell, compare current frame against background
- Calculate pixel change intensity per cell
- If change exceeds threshold → cell is "active"

Step 3 — Panic Pattern Detection
This is your core differentiator:
- Track each cell's activity over a rolling time window (e.g. 3–5 seconds)
- Normal swimming:  cell activates → moves to adjacent cell → moves on
- Panic motion:     cell stays active repeatedly within the same zone
- If a cell triggers continuously for X frames within the window → FLAG as panic

Step 4 — Confidence Filtering
To reduce false alarms:
- Require motion intensity above a minimum threshold
- Require motion to persist for minimum duration (e.g. 3 seconds)
- Ignore single-frame spikes (splashing, jumping)
- Optional: require motion to stay within a 2x2 cell radius (confined area)

Step 5 — Alert Trigger
- Flagged zone is identified by grid coordinates (e.g. C4)
- Alert is sent to lifeguard wearable
- Wearable vibrates + displays grid zone location
- Visual overlay on monitor highlights the flagged cell in red

